    <stitle>CF 500, CF 600 Steering - Steering Linkage - Removal and Installation</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="20">
        <title>Removal and Installation</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Tie Rod End - Outer</title>
            <table id="t1103002">
                <title>Special Tool</title>
                <tgroup cols="2">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.16*"/>
                    <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="0.84*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <graphic filename="../figST1/ST1263A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="152px"
                                         scalefitheight="112px"/>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Remover, Steering Arm</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Install a new front wheel spindle tie rod if the ball stud is loose in the socket or the front
                        wheel spindle tie rod is bent. Install a new front suspension steering ball stud dust seal if
                        any nicks, cuts or tears are present. Do not attempt to straighten a bent front wheel spindle
                        tie rod.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>RH front wheel spindle tie rod shown, LH front wheel spindle tie rod similar.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the wheel and tire assembly. For additional information, refer to
                    <exhotlnk document="../S17/S17002.htm" bookname="S17002">Wheels and Tires in S17002</exhotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen the adjusting sleeve clamp nut.</para>
                <para>&#8226; Tighten to 80 Nm (59 lb-ft).</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103003" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1147A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cotter pin and castellated tie-rod end nut. Discard the cotter pin.</para>
                <para>&#8226; To install, tighten to 115 Nm (85 lb-ft).</para>
                <para>&#8226; Install a new cotter pin.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103004" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1148A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using the special tool, disconnect the front wheel spindle tie rod.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103005" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../fign00/N0024221.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the front wheel spindle tie rod.</para>
                <para>&#8226; Note the number of turns required to remove the front wheel spindle tie rod.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To install, reverse the removal procedure.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the toe-in and clear vision settings. For additional information, refer to
                    <exhotlnk document="../S03/S03014.htm" bookname="S03014">Suspension System in S03014</exhotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Sector Shaft Arm Drag Link</title>
            <table id="t1103002">
                <title>Special Tool</title>
                <tgroup cols="2">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.16*"/>
                    <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="0.84*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <graphic filename="../figST1/ST1263A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="152px"
                                         scalefitheight="112px"/>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Remover, Steering Arm</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Install a new steering sector shaft arm drag link if the ball stud is loose in the socket or
                        if the steering sector shaft arm drag link is bent. Install a new front suspension steering ball
                        stud dust seal if any nicks, cuts or tears are present. Do not attempt to straighten a steering
                        sector shaft arm drag link.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cotter pin and castellated steering sector shaft arm drag link-to-sector gear
                    shaft arm nut. Discard the cotter pin.
                </para>
                <para>&#8226; Tighten to 115 Nm (85 lb-ft).</para>
                <para>&#8226; Install a new cotter pin.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103006" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1165A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using the special tool, disconnect the steering sector shaft arm drag link from the
                    steering gear sector shaft arm.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103007" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../fign00/N0024217.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cotter pin and castellated steering sector shaft arm drag link-to-spindle
                    nut. Discard the cotter pin.
                </para>
                <para>&#8226; Tighten to 175 Nm (129 lb-ft).</para>
                <para>&#8226; Install a new cotter pin.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103008" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1167A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using the special tool, disconnect and remove the steering sector shaft arm drag link.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103009" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../fign00/N0024218.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When installing a new steering sector shaft arm drag link, equalize the thread engagement of
                        the short and long tie-rod ends in the adjusting sleeve. This will provide an approximate toe-in
                        setting.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The steering linkage must be installed with the steering gear on center (&#177; 45 degrees of
                        the power steering gear input shaft and control). The ball studs must be seated in the tapered
                        hole to prevent rotation while tightening the nuts.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To install, reverse the removal procedure.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the toe-in and clear vision settings. For additional information, refer to
                    <exhotlnk document="../S03/S03014.htm" bookname="S03014">Suspension System in S03014</exhotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Sector Shaft Arm</title>
            <table id="t1103002">
                <title>Special Tool</title>
                <tgroup cols="2">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.16*"/>
                    <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="0.84*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <graphic filename="../figST1/ST1263A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="152px"
                                         scalefitheight="112px"/>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Remover, Steering Arm</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Install a new steering gear sector shaft arm if it is bent. If the steering gear sector shaft
                        arm is bent, check remainder of the steering linkage system for signs of damage. Replace any
                        damaged steering linkage parts as required. Do not attempt to straighten the steering gear
                        sector shaft arm or any other steering linkage components.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cotter pin and castellated steering sector shaft arm drag link-to-sector gear
                    shaft arm nut. Discard the cotter pin.
                </para>
                <para>&#8226; Tighten to 115 Nm (85 lb-ft).</para>
                <para>&#8226; Install a new cotter pin.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103010" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1165A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using the special tool, disconnect the steering sector shaft arm drag link. Position the
                    steering sector shaft arm drag link aside.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103011" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../fign00/N0024217.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove and discard the steering gear sector shaft arm nut and bolt.</para>
                <para>&#8226; To install, tighten to 350 Nm (259 lb-ft).</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103012" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1174A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not use heat or pound on the steering gear sector shaft arm or sector shaft as damage can
                        result. These components must be installed new rather than repaired if they are damaged.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using the special tool, remove the steering gear sector shaft arm.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103013" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../fign00/N0024222.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The wheels should be in a straight-ahead position.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To install, reverse the removal procedure.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the toe-in and clear vision settings. For additional information, refer to
                    <exhotlnk document="../S03/S03014.htm" bookname="S03014">Suspension System in S03014</exhotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Spindle Steering Arm</title>
            <table id="t1103002">
                <title>Special Tool</title>
                <tgroup cols="2">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.16*"/>
                    <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="0.84*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <graphic filename="../figST1/ST1263A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="152px"
                                         scalefitheight="112px"/>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Remover, Steering Arm</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Drag link spindle steering arm shown, LH and RH spindle steering arms similar.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cotter pin and castellated steering sector shaft arm drag link-to-spindle
                    nut. Discard the cotter pin.
                </para>
                <para>&#8226; Tighten to 175 Nm (129 lb-ft).</para>
                <para>&#8226; Install a new cotter pin.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103014" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1167A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using the special tool, disconnect the steering sector shaft arm drag link.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103015" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../fign00/N0024218.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cotter pin and castellated spindle steering arm nut.</para>
                <para>&#8226; To install, tighten to 550 Nm (404 lb-ft).</para>
                <para>&#8226; Install a new cotter pin.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103016" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1256A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the spindle steering arm.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103017" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1257A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the key.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1103018" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figdg1/DG1258A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The spindle hole is slotted to align the spindle steering arm with the front wheel spindle. Be
                        sure that the key is flush with the face of the spindle steering arm.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To install, reverse the removal procedure.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the toe-in and clear vision settings. For additional information, refer to
                    <exhotlnk document="../S03/S03014.htm" bookname="S03014">Suspension System in S03014</exhotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
